{{Quote|There's two things about ''Star Wars'' that are really very powerful. One is the technology, a lot of it was new; and secondly, the storytelling was based on Joseph Campbell and the structure of myth.|Jack Klaff|<ref name="SWI163">{{InsiderCite|163|My Star Wars}}</ref>}}
'''Jack Klaff''' is a [[Wikipedia:South Africa|South African]] academic, actor, director, and writer who portrayed [[John D. Branon]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']]. Klaff began his acting career with the Brook Theater in Johannesburg. By [[1976]], he moved to the [[Wikipedia:United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]. He joined the [[Wikipedia:Royal Shakespeare Academy|Royal Shakespeare Academy]] in [[1978]]. His television and movie credits outside of ''Star Wars'' include roles in [[Wikipedia:For Your Eyes Only (film)|''For Your Eyes Only'']], [[Wikipedia:Space: 1999|''Space: 1999'']] and [[Wikipedia:Red Dwarf|''Red Dwarf'']].

For years, many fans believed that [[Wedge Antilles]]'s line "That's impossible, even for a computer" during the [[Battle of Yavin]] briefing scenes was delivered by Klaff. Since Wedge was played by [[Denis Lawson]] in all other scenes, the actor and character in this sequence was sometimes referred to as "Fake Wedge." [[Pablo Hidalgo]] revealed on his blog that [[Colin Higgins]] was in this scene, and identified Higgins as "Fake Wedge".<ref name="Blog">{{Blog|pablog|37|The Hunt for the Fake Wedge}}</ref>

